/a></th><td class=3D"infobox-data"><span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp=
;</span>1.8288&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=
=3D"Metre">m</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>A <b>fathom</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_m=
easurement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Units of measurement">unit</a> o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length" title=3D"Length">length<=
/a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_unit" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Imperial unit">imperial</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_customary_units" title=3D"United States =
customary units">U.S. customary</a> systems equal to 6 feet (1.8288&nbsp;m)=
, used especially for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_soundi=
ng" title=3D"Depth sounding">measuring the depth of water</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-britannica11_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-britannica11-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The fathom is neithe=
r an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_standard" title=
=3D"International standard">international standard</a> (SI) unit, nor an in=
ternationally accepted non-SI unit. Historically, it was the maritime measu=
re of depth in the English-speaking world but, apart from within the US, ch=
arts now use metres.
</p><p>There are two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard" title=
=3D"Yard">yards</a> (6 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(lengt=
h)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Foot (length)">feet</a>) in an imperial =
fathom.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-britannica11_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-britannica11-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Originally the span of a man's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arm=
_span" title=3D"Arm span">outstretched arms</a>, the size of a fathom has v=
aried slightly depending on whether it was defined as a thousandth of an <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautical_mile" title=3D"Nautical mil=
e">(Admiralty) nautical mile</a> or as a multiple of the imperial <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard" title=3D"Yard">yard</a>. Formerly, =
the term was used for any of several units of length varying around 5=E2=80=
=93<span class=3D"frac">5<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num=
">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> feet (1.5=E2=80=931.=
7&nbsp;m).
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Etymology"></span>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The term (pronounced <span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class=
=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span style=3D"b=
order-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: primary stress follows">=
=CB=88</span><span title=3D"'f' in 'find'">f</span><span title=3D"/=C3=A6/:=
 'a' in 'bad'">=C3=A6</span><span title=3D"/=C3=B0/: 'th' in 'this'">=C3=B0=
</span><span title=3D"/=C9=99/: 'a' in 'about'">=C9=99</span><span title=3D=
"'m' in 'my'">m</span></span>/</a></span></span>) derives (via <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_English_language" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Middle English language">Middle English</a> <i>fathme</i>) from t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English_language" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Old English language">Old English</a> <i>f=C3=A6=C3=
=B0m</i>, which is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognate_(lingui=
stics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cognate (linguistics)">cognate</a> w=
ith the Danish word <i>favn</i> and means "embracing arms" or "pair of outs=
tretched arms". It is maybe also cognate with the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Old_High_German" title=3D"Old High German">Old High German<=
/a> word "fadum", which has the same meaning and also means "yarn (original=
ly stretching between the outstretched fingertips)".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-oed=
_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#c=
ite_note-oed-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
athom#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Fathom#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Forms">Forms</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Forms"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Greek"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"=
Orguia"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Greek_fathom"></span><span clas=
s=3D"anchor" id=3D"Greek_fathoms"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ancient_fathoms">Ancient fa=
thoms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Ancient fathoms"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek_units_of_meas=
urement" title=3D"Ancient Greek units of measurement">Ancient Greek measure=
</a> known as the <b>orguia</b> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
ncient_Greek_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient Greek languag=
e">Ancient Greek</a>: <span lang=3D"grc">=E1=BD=80=CF=81=CE=B3=CF=85=CE=B9=
=CE=AC</span>, <i>orgyi=C3=A1</i>, <small><abbr title=3D"literally">lit</ab=
br>.</small><span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>"outstretched") is usually =
translated as "fathom".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine_Empire" title=3D"Byzantine =
Empire">Byzantine period</a>, this <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Byzantine_units_of_measurement" title=3D"Byzantine units of measurement">u=
nit</a> came in two forms: a "simple orguia" (<span title=3D"Ancient Greek =
(to 1453)-language text"><span lang=3D"grc">=E1=BC=81=CF=80=CE=BB=E1=BD=B4 =
=E1=BD=80=CF=81=CE=B3=CF=85=CE=B9=CE=AC</span></span>, <i>hapl=C4=93 orgui=
=C3=A1</i>) roughly equivalent to the old Greek fathom (6 <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byzantine_units#Length" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Byzantine units">Byzantine feet</a>, <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><sp=
an style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891.87</span><span class=3D"nowrap"=
>&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meter_(unit)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Meter (unit)">m</a>) and an "imperial" (<span tit=
le=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language text"><span lang=3D"grc">=CE=B2=CE=
=B1=CF=83=CE=B9=CE=BB=CE=B9=CE=BA=E1=BD=B4</span></span>, <i>basilik=C4=93<=
/i>) or "geometric orguia" (<span title=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language=
 text"><span lang=3D"grc">=CE=B3=CE=B5=CF=89=CE=BC=CE=B5=CF=84=CF=81=CE=B9=
=CE=BA=E1=BD=B4 =E1=BD=80=CF=81=CE=B3=CF=85=CE=B9=CE=AC</span></span>, <i>g=
e=C5=8Dmetrik=C4=93 orgui=C3=A1</i>) that was one-eighth longer (6 feet and=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palmspan" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Palmspan">span</a>, <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D=
"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=892.10</span><span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</sp=
an>m).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-9"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"International_fathom">Inter=
national fathom</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DFathom&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Intern=
ational fathom"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>One international fathom is equal to:
</p>
<ul><li>1.8288 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Met=
re">metres</a> exactly (Official international definition of the fathom)<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"British_fathom">British fat=
hom</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: British fathom"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Admiralty" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"British Admiralty">British Admiralty</a> defined a f=
athom to be a thousandth of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nau=
tical_mile" title=3D"Nautical mile">imperial nautical mile</a> (which was 6=
,080&nbsp;ft) or 6.08 feet (1.85&nbsp;m). In practice, the "warship fathom"=
 of exactly 6 feet (1.8&nbsp;m) was used in Britain and the United States.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Fenna_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-Fenna-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> No conflict between=
 the definitions existed in practice,<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template =
Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation neede=
d"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 20=
23)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> since depths on imperial nautica=
l charts were indicated in feet if less than 30 feet (9.1&nbsp;m) and in fa=
thoms for depths greater than that. Until the 19th century in England, the =
length of the fathom was more variable: from <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-i=
nline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"fra=
c">5<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<s=
pan class=3D"den">2</span></span>&nbsp;feet on merchant vessels to either 5=
 or 7 feet (1.5 or 2.1&nbsp;m) on fishing vessels (from <link rel=3D"mw-ded=
uplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027">1.7 to =
1.5 or 2.1&nbsp;m).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Fenna_11-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-Fenna-11"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_definitions">Other de=
finitions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFa=
thom&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Other defini=
tions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>Other definitions of fathom include:
</p>
<ul><li>1.828804&nbsp;m (Obsolete measurement of the fathom based on the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/US_survey_foot" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"US survey foot">US survey foot</a>, only for use of historical a=
nd legacy applications)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>2 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard" title=3D"Yard">yards</=
a> exactly</li>
<li>18 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hand_(unit)" title=3D"Hand =
(unit)">hands</a></li></ul>
<p>One metre is about 0.5468 fathoms.
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_yard_a=
nd_pound" title=3D"International yard and pound">international yard and pou=
nd</a> agreement of 1959, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit=
ed_States" title=3D"United States">United States</a>, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" title=3D"Australia">Australia</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada" title=3D"Canada">Canada</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Zealand" title=3D"New Zealand">New=
 Zealand</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Africa" title=
=3D"South Africa">South Africa</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a> defin=
ed the length of the international yard to be exactly 0.9144 <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">metre</a>. In 1959, the U=
nited States kept the US survey foot as definition for the fathom.
</p><p>In October 2019, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._N=
ational_Geodetic_Survey" title=3D"U.S. National Geodetic Survey">U.S. Natio=
nal Geodetic Survey</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Na=
tional_Institute_of_Standards_and_Technology" title=3D"National Institute o=
f Standards and Technology">National Institute of Standards and Technology<=
/a> announced their joint intent to retire the U.S. survey foot, with effec=
t from the end of 2022. The fathom in U.S. Customary units is thereafter de=
fined based on the International 1959 foot, giving the length of the fathom=
 as exactly 1.8288 metres in the United States as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cit=
e_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Derived_units">Derived unit=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Derived units"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>At one time, a <i>quarter</i> meant one-quarter of a fathom.<sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references t=
o reliable sources. (December 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>A <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cable_length" title=3D=
"Cable length">cable length</a></i>, based on the length of a ship's cable,=
 has been variously reckoned as equal to 100 or 120 fathoms.<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to rel=
iable sources. (December 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
