</div></div>
<p>Most modern nautical charts indicate depth in metres. However, the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naval_Oceanographic_Office" title=3D"Na=
val Oceanographic Office">U.S. Hydrographic Office</a> uses feet and fathom=
s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Nautical_chart" title=3D"Nautical chart">nautical chart</a> wi=
ll always explicitly indicate the units of depth used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite=
_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>To measure the depth of shallow waters, boatmen used a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sounding_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"S=
ounding line">sounding line</a> containing fathom points, some marked and o=
thers in between, called <i>deeps</i>, unmarked but estimated by the user.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Water near the coast and not too =
deep to be fathomed by a hand sounding line was referred to as <i>in soundi=
ngs</i> or <i>on soundings</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-19"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The area offshore beyond the 100 fathom line, too deep to be fathomed by a=
 hand sounding line, was referred to as <i>out of soundings</i> or <i>off s=
oundings</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <i>deep-sea lead<=
/i>, the heaviest of sounding leads, was used in water exceeding 100 fathom=
s in depth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This technique has been superseded by sonic <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Echo_sounding" title=3D"Echo sounding">depth finders</a> f=
or measuring mechanically the depth of water beneath a ship, one version of=
 which is the <i>Fathometer</i> (trademark).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-22=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> The record made by such a device is a <i>fathogram</i>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Fathom#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <i>fathom line</i> or <i>fathom curv=
e</i>, a usually sinuous line on a nautical chart, joins all points having =
the same depth of water, thereby indicating the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Contour_line" title=3D"Contour line">contour</a> of the ocean=
 floor.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some extensive flat areas of the sea bottom with constant depth are =
known by their fathom number, like the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Broad_Fourteens" title=3D"Broad Fourteens">Broad Fourteens</a> or the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Forties" title=3D"Long Fortie=
s">Long Forties</a>, both in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
orth_Sea" title=3D"North Sea">North Sea</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Line_length">Line length</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Line length"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The components of a commercial fisherman's <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Setline" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Setline">setline</a> we=
re measured in fathoms. The rope called a <i>groundline</i>, used to form t=
he main line of a setline, was usually provided in bundles of 300 fathoms. =
A single 50-fathom (300&nbsp;ft; 91&nbsp;m) <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionar=
y.org/wiki/skein#en-n-1" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:skein">skein</a> of =
this rope was referred to as a <i>line</i>. Especially in Pacific coast fis=
heries, the setline was composed of units called <i>skates</i>, each consis=
ting of several hundred fathoms of groundline, with <a href=3D"https://en.w=
iktionary.org/wiki/gangion" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:gangion">gangions=
</a> and hooks attached. A <i>tuck seine</i> or <i>tuck net</i> about 70 fa=
thoms (420&nbsp;ft; 130&nbsp;m) long, and very deep in the middle, was used=
 to take fish from a larger <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seine_=
fishing" title=3D"Seine fishing">seine</a>.
</p><p>A <i>line</i> attached to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Whaling" title=3D"Whaling">whaling</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Harpoon" title=3D"Harpoon">harpoon</a> was about 150 fathoms (900&nbs=
p;ft; 270&nbsp;m). A <i>forerunner</i>=E2=80=94a piece of cloth tied on a s=
hip's log line some fathoms from the outboard end=E2=80=94marked the limit =
of drift line.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <i>kite</i> was =
a drag, towed under water at any depth up to about 40 fathoms (240&nbsp;ft;=
 73&nbsp;m), which upon striking bottom, was upset and rose to the surface.
</p><p>A <i>shot</i>, one of the forged lengths of chain joined by shackles=
 to form an anchor cable, was usually 15 fathoms (90&nbsp;ft; 27&nbsp;m).<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A <i>shackle</i>, a length of cable or chain equal to <link rel=3D"m=
w-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><s=
pan class=3D"frac">12<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1<=
/span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> fathoms (75&nbsp;ft; 22.=
9&nbsp;m).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1949, the British n=
avy redefined the shackle to be 15 fathoms (90&nbsp;ft; 27&nbsp;m).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Jerrard1986_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-Jerrard1986-28"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finland" title=3D"Finla=
nd">Finnish</a> fathom (<i>syli</i>) is occasionally used: <link rel=3D"mw-=
deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><spa=
n class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">1=
000</span></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautical_mile" t=
itle=3D"Nautical mile">nautical mile</a> or <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-in=
line-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac=
"><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">100</span></span=
> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cable_length" title=3D"Cable len=
gth">cable length</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Burial">Burial</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Burial"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burial_at_sea" title=3D"Buria=
l at sea">burial at sea</a> (where the body is weighted to force it to the =
bottom) requires a minimum of six fathoms of water. This is the origin of t=
he phrase "<i>to deep six</i>" as meaning to discard, or dispose of.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fathom#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The phrase is echoed in Shakespeare's <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/The_Tempest" title=3D"The Tempest">The Tempest</a></i>, where=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ariel_(The_Tempest)" title=3D"Ari=
el (The Tempest)">Ariel</a> tells <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Ferdinand_(The_Tempest)" title=3D"Ferdinand (The Tempest)">Ferdinand</a>, "=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_Fathom_Five_(Tempest)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Full Fathom Five (Tempest)">Full fathom five</a> =
thy father lies".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"On_land">On land</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFathom&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: On land"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Until early in the 20th century, it was the unit used to measure the dep=
th of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mining" title=3D"Mining">min=
es</a> (mineral extraction) in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/United_Kingdom" title=3D"United Kingdom">United Kingdom</a>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fath=
om#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Miners also use it as a unit of area equal to =
6 feet square (3.34 m<sup>2</sup>) in the plane of a vein.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-oed_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fa=
thom#cite_note-oed-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In Britain, it can mean the quantity of wo=
od in a pile of any length measuring 6 feet (1.8&nbsp;m) square in cross se=
ction.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-oed_2-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fathom#cite_note-oed-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Europe" title=3D"Central Europe">Central E=
urope</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klafter" title=3D"K=
lafter">klafter</a> was the corresponding unit of comparable length, as was=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toise" title=3D"Toise">toise<=
/a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/France" title=3D"France">Fr=
ance</a>. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungary" title=3D"Hun=
gary">Hungary</a> the square fathom ("<a href=3D"https://hu.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/%C3%96l#Magyarorsz.C3.A1gon" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"hu:=C3=96l">n=C3=
=A9gysz=C3=B6g=C3=B6l</a>") is still in use as an unofficial measure of lan=
d area, primarily for small lots suitable for construction.<sup class=3D"no=
print Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"The text near this tag may nee=
d clarification or removal of jargon. (September 2016)">clarification neede=
d</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
